---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import ChapterNav from "../components/ChapterNav.astro";
---

<Layout title="API Key Management & Encryption - Abaki">
    <main class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 py-12 md:py-20">
        <a
            href="/abaki-overview"
            class="mb-8 inline-flex items-center text-sm font-medium text-indigo-400 hover:text-indigo-300"
        >
            <span class="mr-2">&larr;</span>
            Back to Abaki Overview
        </a>

        <article>
            <header class="mb-12">
                <h1
                    class="mb-4 text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight sm:text-5xl text-white"
                >
                    API Key Management & Encryption
                </h1>
                <p class="text-lg text-gray-400">
                    Secure storage of sensitive GitHub and AI provider tokens
                    using AES encryption
                </p>
            </header>

            <section class="prose prose-invert max-w-none space-y-8">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Overview</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
                        Abaki integrates with external services (GitHub, Google
                        Gemini AI) that require API keys for authentication.
                        Storing these keys in plain text would be a catastrophic
                        security vulnerability. This module encrypts sensitive
                        tokens at rest in the database, decrypts them only when
                        needed for API calls, and provides secure key rotation
                        support.
                    </p>
                    <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mt-4">
                        The implementation uses AES-256 encryption with a
                        derived initialization vector, enabling both secure
                        storage and deterministic encryption (required for
                        database queries on encrypted fields).
                    </p>
                </div>

                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">
                        Learning Journey
                    </h2>
                    <div class="space-y-3 text-gray-300">
                        <div>
                            <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-1">
                                🔐 Challenge 1: Understanding Encryption
                            </h3>
                            <p>
                                Initially didn't understand the difference
                                between symmetric and asymmetric encryption.
                                Learned why AES (symmetric) is appropriate for
                                this use case where the server both encrypts and
                                decrypts data.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-1">
                                🔑 Challenge 2: Key Management
                            </h3>
                            <p>
                                Where do we store the encryption key itself?
                                Can't store it in the code (security risk) or
                                the database (circular problem). Solution:
                                Configuration/environment variables with proper
                                access controls.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-1">
                                🔄 Challenge 3: Deterministic Encryption
                            </h3>
                            <p>
                                Standard encryption uses random IVs, making it
                                impossible to query encrypted fields. Needed
                                deterministic encryption (same plaintext → same
                                ciphertext) to support lookups. This required
                                deriving a fixed IV from the encryption key.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-1">
                                🛡️ Challenge 4: Backward Compatibility
                            </h3>
                            <p>
                                Had to handle transitioning from unencrypted to
                                encrypted keys without breaking the system.
                                Implemented fallback logic that treats
                                non-Base64 strings as plaintext for old records.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-1">
                                ✅ Key Learning
                            </h3>
                            <p>
                                Security requires thinking multiple layers deep.
                                Never store credentials in code, always separate
                                encryption keys from encrypted data, and always
                                provide migration paths for security updates.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">
                        Key Code Implementation
                    </h2>

                    <div class="mb-6">
                        <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-3">
                            AES Encryption Helper
                        </h3>
                        <div
                            class="rounded-lg bg-gray-900 border border-gray-700 overflow-hidden"
                        >
                            <pre
                                class="text-gray-300 text-sm p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code>{`// Helpers/EncryptionHelper.cs
using System.Security.Cryptography;
using System.Text;

public class EncryptionHelper
{
    private readonly byte[] _key;
    private readonly byte[] _iv;

    public EncryptionHelper(string base64Key)
    {
        _key = Convert.FromBase64String(base64Key);

        // Derive a FIXED 16-byte IV from the key
        // This enables deterministic encryption for database queries
        using var sha = SHA256.Create();
        _iv = sha.ComputeHash(_key).Take(16).ToArray();
    }

    public string Encrypt(string plainText)
    {
        if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(plainText)) 
            return plainText;

        using var aes = Aes.Create();
        aes.Key = _key;
        aes.IV = _iv;  // Fixed IV for determinism

        using var encryptor = aes.CreateEncryptor(aes.Key, aes.IV);
        using var ms = new MemoryStream();
        using (var cs = new CryptoStream(ms, encryptor, CryptoStreamMode.Write))
        using (var sw = new StreamWriter(cs))
        {
            sw.Write(plainText);
        }

        // Return Base64-encoded ciphertext
        return Convert.ToBase64String(ms.ToArray());
    }

    public string Decrypt(string cipherText)
    {
        if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(cipherText)) 
            return cipherText;

        // Handle backward compatibility: older rows might be plaintext
        Span<byte> buffer = stackalloc byte[cipherText.Length];
        if (!Convert.TryFromBase64String(cipherText, buffer, out var bytesWritten))
        {
            // Not Base64 → treat as plaintext (old unencrypted record)
            return cipherText;
        }

        try
        {
            using var aes = Aes.Create();
            aes.Key = _key;
            aes.IV = _iv;  // Same fixed IV

            var cipherBytes = buffer.Slice(0, bytesWritten).ToArray();

            using var ms = new MemoryStream(cipherBytes);
            using var cs = new CryptoStream(ms, aes.CreateDecryptor(), CryptoStreamMode.Read);
            using var sr = new StreamReader(cs);
            
            return sr.ReadToEnd();
        }
        catch (CryptographicException ex)
        {
            throw new Exception("Decryption failed. Key may be invalid.", ex);
        }
    }
}`}</code></pre>
                        </div>
                        <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mt-2">
                            The fixed IV is derived from the key using SHA-256,
                            ensuring the same plaintext always produces the same
                            ciphertext. This enables database queries like WHERE
                            Key = encryptedValue.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <div class="mb-6">
                        <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-3">
                            Key Service with Encryption
                        </h3>
                        <div
                            class="rounded-lg bg-gray-900 border border-gray-700 overflow-hidden"
                        >
                            <pre
                                class="text-gray-300 text-sm p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code>{`// Services/KeyService.cs
public class KeyService : IKeyService
{
    private readonly AbakiDb _db;
    private readonly ILogger<KeyService> _logger;
    private readonly EncryptionHelper _encryptionHelper;

    public KeyService(AbakiDb db, ILogger<KeyService> logger, EncryptionHelper encryptionHelper)
    {
        _db = db;
        _logger = logger;
        _encryptionHelper = encryptionHelper;
    }

    public async Task AddAsync(AIAPIKey key)
    {
        if (key == null)
            throw new BadRequestException("Key cannot be null.");

        if (string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(key.Key))
            throw new BadRequestException("Key value cannot be empty.");

        _logger.LogInformation("Adding new API key for provider: {Provider}", key.ProviderId);

        // ENCRYPT the key before saving to database
        key.Key = _encryptionHelper.Encrypt(key.Key);

        _db.AIAPIKeys.Add(key);
        await _db.SaveChangesAsync();

        _logger.LogInformation("API key added and encrypted for provider: {Provider}", key.ProviderId);
    }

    public async Task<AIAPIKey?> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _db.AIAPIKeys.FindAsync(id);
    }

    public string GetDecryptedKeyAsync(int keyId)
    {
        var key = await GetByIdAsync(keyId);
        if (key == null)
            throw new NotFoundExceptionC($"API key {keyId} not found.");

        // DECRYPT when returning to caller
        var decrypted = _encryptionHelper.Decrypt(key.Key);
        
        _logger.LogDebug("Key decrypted for provider: {Provider}", key.ProviderId);
        
        return decrypted;
    }
}`}</code></pre>
                        </div>
                        <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mt-2">
                            Keys are encrypted on the way in and decrypted on
                            the way out. The plaintext token is only in memory
                            when actively being used for API calls.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <div>
                        <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-3">
                            Using Encrypted Keys in API Calls
                        </h3>
                        <div
                            class="rounded-lg bg-gray-900 border border-gray-700 overflow-hidden"
                        >
                            <pre
                                class="text-gray-300 text-sm p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code>{`// RepoService.cs - Using encrypted tokens
public async Task SetupWebhookAsync(int repoId, string webhookUrl)
{
    var repo = await _db.Repos.FindAsync(repoId);
    if (repo == null)
        throw new NotFoundExceptionC($"Repository {repoId} not found.");

    if (repo.KeyId == null)
        throw new BadRequestException("No GitHub token configured for this repo.");

    // Get encrypted key from database
    var encryptedKey = await _keyService.GetByIdAsync(repo.KeyId.Value);
    if (encryptedKey == null)
        throw new BadRequestException("GitHub token not found.");

    // DECRYPT the token
    var decryptedToken = _encryptionHelper.Decrypt(encryptedKey.Key);

    // Use the decrypted token with Octokit
    var client = new GitHubClient(new ProductHeaderValue("Abaki"))
    {
        Credentials = new Credentials(decryptedToken)
    };

    try
    {
        // Make GitHub API call with decrypted token
        var hook = await client.Repository.Hooks.Create(
            repo.Owner,
            repo.RepositoryName,
            new NewRepositoryHook("web") { /* ... */ }
        );

        repo.WebhookActive = true;
        await _db.SaveChangesAsync();

        _logger.LogInformation("Webhook setup successful for {Repo}", repo.Name);
    }
    finally
    {
        // Token is no longer needed and is eligible for GC
    }
}`}</code></pre>
                        </div>
                        <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mt-2">
                            The decrypted token exists only in the local
                            variable scope. Once the method exits, it's garbage
                            collected and no longer in memory.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">
                        Security Considerations
                    </h2>
                    <div class="space-y-3 text-gray-300">
                        <div
                            class="p-4 rounded-lg bg-indigo-500/10 border border-indigo-500/30"
                        >
                            <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-2">
                                🔑 Encryption Key Management
                            </h3>
                            <p>
                                The master encryption key is stored in
                                configuration (appsettings.json for dev,
                                environment variables for production). It's NOT
                                committed to version control.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div
                            class="p-4 rounded-lg bg-indigo-500/10 border border-indigo-500/30"
                        >
                            <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-2">
                                🔄 Deterministic Encryption
                            </h3>
                            <p>
                                Uses a fixed IV derived from the encryption key.
                                Enables database queries on encrypted fields
                                (e.g., WHERE Key = encryptedValue) for
                                uniqueness checks, while still maintaining
                                encryption.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div
                            class="p-4 rounded-lg bg-indigo-500/10 border border-indigo-500/30"
                        >
                            <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-2">
                                🛡️ In-Memory Security
                            </h3>
                            <p>
                                Decrypted tokens exist only when actively
                                needed. They're never logged, never returned to
                                clients, and are garbage collected as soon as
                                the API call completes.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div
                            class="p-4 rounded-lg bg-indigo-500/10 border border-indigo-500/30"
                        >
                            <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-2">
                                ↩️ Backward Compatibility
                            </h3>
                            <p>
                                The decryption method checks if data is
                                Base64-encoded. If not, it treats it as
                                plaintext, allowing gradual migration from
                                unencrypted to encrypted keys without downtime.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">
                        Technology Stack
                    </h2>
                    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
                        {
                            [
                                "C#",
                                "AES-256 Encryption",
                                "System.Security.Cryptography",
                                "SHA-256",
                                "Base64 Encoding",
                                "Configuration Management",
                            ].map((tech) => (
                                <span class="rounded-full border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-500/10 px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-indigo-300">
                                    {tech}
                                </span>
                            ))
                        }
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">
                        Results & Impact
                    </h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
                        The encryption system provides:
                    </p>
                    <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 mt-3">
                        <li class="flex items-start">
                            <span class="text-indigo-400 mr-3">✓</span>
                            <span
                                ><strong>Data Protection at Rest:</strong> Compromised
                                databases don't expose API tokens</span
                            >
                        </li>
                        <li class="flex items-start">
                            <span class="text-indigo-400 mr-3">✓</span>
                            <span
                                ><strong>Industry-Standard Encryption:</strong> AES-256
                                is trusted by government and enterprise</span
                            >
                        </li>
                        <li class="flex items-start">
                            <span class="text-indigo-400 mr-3">✓</span>
                            <span
                                ><strong>Database Queryability:</strong> Deterministic
                                encryption allows searches on encrypted fields</span
                            >
                        </li>
                        <li class="flex items-start">
                            <span class="text-indigo-400 mr-3">✓</span>
                            <span
                                ><strong>Key Rotation Support:</strong> Ability to
                                re-encrypt all keys when the master key changes</span
                            >
                        </li>
                        <li class="flex items-start">
                            <span class="text-indigo-400 mr-3">✓</span>
                            <span
                                ><strong>Zero Token Logging:</strong> Sensitive data
                                never appears in logs or error messages</span
                            >
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </section>
            <ChapterNav
                prevLink="/abaki-database"
                prevText="Database Architecture"
                nextLink="/abaki-logging"
                nextText="Activity Logging"
            />
        </article>
    </main>
</Layout>
